{
  "doc_id": "6803",
  "text": "For each (type) specimen microscope slides were made. A small piece (<1 cm) of the distal part of the octocoral was dissolved in a 4% household bleach solution to isolate sclerites. The sclerites were washed with tap water (five times), followed by the same number of wash steps with demineralised water. Sclerites were dried on a hot plate and subsequently embedded in Euparal for visualisation with a Leica DM LB2 light microscope. In addition, sclerites of specimens that represent specific clades or needed further morphological investigations were mounted on SEM stubs and coated with Pd/Au for imaging on a JEOL JSM6490LV scanning electron microscope operated at high vacuum at 10 kV. Consequently, microscope slides and SEM images were used to assign specimens to the nominal genera according to the following key based on [CITATION_1] .",
  "correct_citation": {
